      "content": "First, we'll ensure the class definition includes the `forward` method. Then, we'll incorporate a mechanism to selectively apply the sparsity penalty based on the existence of the `mask` tensor. Within the `forward` method, we'll element-wise multiply the mask with the logits before calculating the Cross-Entropy loss using the negative log likelihood of the targets. The sparsity penalty will be calculated as the sum of the penalized logits times the sparsity weight, normalized by the total number of elements in the logits and masks. Here's the relevant updated code:\n\n```python\ndef forward(self, logits, targets, mask):\n    loss = F.cross_entropy(logits, targets, reduction='mean')\n    \n    sparsity_penalty = 0.0\n    if mask is not None and mask.any():\n        sparsity_penalty = torch.sum(mask * logits) * self.sparsity_weight / (logits.numel() * mask.numel())\n    \n    return loss + sparsity_penalty\n```\n\nNow your test case should succeed. The updated `SparsityLoss` class includes the proper handling for the mask tensor and should pass the provided test case.",
